<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former racing champ and auto designer Carroll
Shelby left a Los Angeles hospital in high spirits after a heart
transplant.
   Shelby, 67, was released Friday from Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center, where he had surgery June 8.
   ``Everything is fine. It couldn't have gone better,'' hospital
spokesman Ron Wise said.
   Wise attributed Shelby's excellent spirits to his speedy
recovery.
   ``He acted as if it was no more than a tooth extraction,'' Wise
said.
   Shelby lives on a ranch in Pittsburg, Texas, about 120 miles
northeast of Dallas. He was a three-time U.S. sports car driver of
the year and in the 1960s designed the Cobra muscle car, the first
affordable performance car at $6,000.
   Shelby had been suffering from congestive heart failure for
about a year prior to the transplant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gloria Estefan, recovering from a broken back,
wielded a giant bottle of champagne as she christened a cruise ship.
   Ms. Estefan, the singer for Miami Sound Machine, had words of
support Friday for another Miami-based act _ 2 Live Crew. The
popular rap band should not be censored, she said. A federal judge
in Florida this month deemed the group's album ``As Nasty As They
Wanna Be'' obscene.
   ``To an artist and from the artist's standpoint I feel that we
need to have freedom to be able to express ourselves,'' Ms. Estefan
said.
   Ms. Estefan, injured when her tour bus was hit by a truck in
March, says her recovery is progressing and she is passing time by
writing new songs. But she said it will be some time before she
returns to the stage.
   ``I'm at the writing stage now,'' she said.
   Ms. Estefan christened the $200 million cruise ship Nordic
Empress, operated by Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd. It took her two
attempts to get the bottle of bubbly to shatter.
   At Ms. Estefan's request, Royal Caribbean will donate $25,000 to
the Children's Home Society, which assists abused children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Clint Black is
driving a 1987 Porsche Targa thanks to an idle promise two years
ago from his record producer.
   ``I told Clint, `Kid, you get me a gold record and you can have
my Porsche,''' producer James Stroud said.
   Black's debut album, ``Killin' Time,'' has sold 1.6 million
copies. An album must sell 500,000 copies to go gold.
   Stroud turned over the flashy red set of wheels this week.
   ``I was able to hold off when he went gold, but when he went
platinum (1 million copies), I pretty much had to give it up,''
Stroud said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joan Mondale, wife of former Vice President
Walter Mondale, made her orchestra debut as a narrator with the
Minnesota Sinfonia.
   Mondale, who lives in Minneapolis with her husband, narrated a
performance Friday of ``The Emperor's New Clothes'' and was set for
a second performance Sunday.
   ``I've always thought working with an orchestra would be the
neatest thing in the world,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush praised a new nursery
for babies handicapped by crack and AIDS.
   Mrs. Bush on Friday dedicated Variety House for Children, opened
in New York about a month ago by the Association to Benefit
Children.
   ``So many kids can accomplish what they set out to do if they
have the love and care they need and that's what places like
Variety House are for,'' Mrs. Bush said.
   The nursery will provide a transitional home for up to six
babies until foster parents can be found. It also will eventually
include a day care center for up to 12 children infected with the
HIV virus.
</TEXT>
