<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Lloyd Francis Jr. -- Mercury News; Marc Rankin stocks the Guns
N' Roses display at Tower Records in Mountain View for the third time  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  RECORD; PRODUCT; SALE; MUSIC; STORE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A barrage of headbangers, music collectors and fans hungry for the
just-released Guns N' Roses albums overwhelmed two local music stores early
Tuesday morning, buying hundreds of the long-awaited albums -- the group's
first studio work since 1987's "Appetite for Destruction," which has sales of
14 million and counting.;   A line of more than 500 people wrapped itself
around Tower Records in Campbell waiting for a special midnight to 2 a.m. sale
to buy the first copies of the simultaneously released Guns N' Roses compact
discs and tapes, "Use Your Illusion I" and "Use Your Illusion II," at a
discount. Fans heard the first studio tracks from speakers inside the store
while they stood in line.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOT AS A PISTOL
HUNDREDS WAIT AT MIDNIGHT FOR HIGH-CALIBER ALBUMS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran on page 2B of the Morning Final edition  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "I've been here since 10:30 p.m.," said one of the first buyers at the
Campbell store.;   Fans waved their albums at those still in line, punched
them into car stereos and left the Campbell store parking lot blaring Axl
Rose's shrill tones over speakers cranked to distortion levels.;   A Campbell
store manager estimated 640 albums were sold in less than two hours. In
Mountain View, 460 albums were sold and the store took in about $5,500. Most
of the action at both stores was in the first half hour.;   "It's the biggest
crowd I have ever seen go through this store in 30 minutes," said Bret
Mitchell, manager of the Campbell store.;   Fans have called the stores for
months about the long-awaited albums. With the recent release of the albums'
singles, "You Could Be Mine," the theme song from the movie "Terminator 2,"
and "Don't Cry," along with the controversial and often-violent national tour,
fans have been more persistent than ever.;   Local Tower Records stores opened
their doors at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday, a minute into the final and long-overdue
release date. As a bonus, Tower lowered the price of the two-CD set to $22
until 2 a.m., when doors closed and prices went back to $11.99 per album.;
"We knew there would be fans here, but we weren't prepared for a crowd like
this," said Melissa Wong, a supervisor at the Mountain View Tower Records.;
One of the most popular items was the rare vinyl copy of the two-album set.
The Campbell store sold all of its 30 sets Tuesday morning.;   "They were
picked up right away by collectors who had no intention of opening them,"
Mitchell said. "If we had thought of the collector value those would have, we
would have tripled our order.";   The only one not surprised at the huge
demand for these guaranteed mega-hit albums was Geffen Records, the group's
label, which shipped a record 2 million copies of each album to more than
1,000 record stores nationwide.  </TEXT>
