<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: WILLIE'S SONG -- Fans who want to help Willie Nelson erase his
multimillion-dollar tax bill can purchase his recently released "Who'll Buy My
Memories? (The IRS Tapes)."  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY; MUSIC; FESTIVAL; TAX  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Since Willie Nelson's "Who'll Buy My Memories? (The IRS Tapes)" went on sale
in June, it has sold only 160,000 copies. Under Nelson's unusual arrangement
with the government, the collection of 25 songs must sell at least 4 million
copies if it is to erase the singer-songwriter's tax obligations.;   "You got
to be positive," Nelson said in a telephone interview last week. "It's not
unheard of. I could sell 3 million albums. I've done it before."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AS WILLIE SINGS, IRS HOPES FOR BIG-MONEY HIT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     He hopes sales will improve when the collection is available in music
stores; it is sold now only through phone orders advertised mostly on
late-night television.;   When Nelson was served last year with a $32 million
bill for delinquent taxes -- one of the largest ever presented to an
individual -- it seemed unlikely that anyone, even the cowboy heroes of his
country and western songs, could rescue him.;   But after months of
negotiation with the IRS, Nelson made a deal that allowed him to bring out the
collection -- yours, for a limited time only, for $19.95 (plus $4 for shipping
and handling) by dialing 1-800-IRS-TAPE.;   The collection includes 25
examples of Nelson's Texas twang and acoustic guitar. The plan is to apply at
least 15 cents from every $1 of sales to the musician's back taxes.;
Laurence Goldfein, Nelson's business manager, said $9.95 of every $19.95 goes
to the telemarketing company that is doing the distribution and marketing;
about $2.40 goes to Sony Corp., Nelson's record company, and $1.60 to other
expenses.;   Pieces of the pie; Nelson's cut is $6. Of that, $2 will go toward
taxes he will owe on the recording's expected profits. Three-quarters of what
is left, or $3, goes to the IRS to satisfy the delinquent tax bill, and the
remaining $1 goes into a war chest to pay for the $45 million lawsuit Nelson
filed last year against his former accountants at Price Waterhouse, whom he
contends put him into ill-advised tax shelters.;   "It'll sell a lot better
once it hits the stores," Nelson said.;   Valerie Thornton, an IRS
spokeswoman, sought to play down the unusual aspects of the arrangements with
Nelson.;   "We try to work with taxpayers, not just Mr. Nelson," she said.
"And if we have to come up with some creative payment plan, that's what we're
going to do, because it's in everyone's best interest.";   "I thought they'd
be crazy not to take it," Nelson said. "The very fact they see a way to make a
lot of money real quick made them go for it. They're not interested in sitting
around waiting 10 or 20 years for the money to trickle in.";   In November,
the government seized Nelson's homesteads in three states, padlocked his
recording studio and arranged to auction off his gold records and the family
piano.;   By then, the government had agreed to take about $15 million less
than it originally wanted, but the 58-year-old singer and songwriter was
having trouble coming up with cash.;   Running out of patience, the government
confiscated almost everything but his talent and his beat-up Martin guitar.;
The ailing real estate market in Texas meant the sales of Nelson's property
reduced his debt by less than $2 million. That left Nelson with a seemingly
insurmountable $15 million obligation.;   But Nelson persuaded the IRS's
district office in Austin, Texas, which is handling his case, to make a major
concession in May.;   Tapes squirreled away; It granted him access to 35
years' worth of seized tapes that he had squirreled away in his Spicewood,
Texas, recording studio. Out of that trove, Nelson created "Who'll Buy My
Memories? (The IRS Tapes).";   "I think it's the best stuff I got," Nelson
said.;   Nelson, considered a country music icon, made his reputation as a
maverick and a songwriter. In the early 1960s, his "Night Life" became Ray
Price's theme song, and "Crazy" was a hit for Patsy Cline (and, years later,
for Linda Ronstadt).;   While he also recorded as a singer, his grainy voice
did not fit the increasingly slick style of Nashville productions, and in the
1970s, Nelson moved back to Texas and began recording with more homespun
backup.;   He also began to make "concept albums," in which songs were linked
to tell stories, and in 1975, he released "Red-Headed Stranger," an album
about a traveling preacher that became a million-seller and ushered in a wave
of Texas-based "outlaw" country music.;   "The Outlaws," a sampler with
Nelson, Waylon Jennings, Tompall Glaser and Jessi Colter released in 1976,
also sold a million copies. And in 1978, Nelson released "Stardust," an album
of pop standards that also became a million-seller.;   Open about tax woes;
Nelson said he had no qualms about making his tax problems a prominent part of
the pitch. "It's been all over the scandal sheets. So why not take advantage
of all that advertising?" he asked.;   Despite the hasty effort to produce and
market the album, Nelson indicated that he was not letting the tax bill take
over his life.;   "There are more serious problems in life than financial
ones, and I've had a lot of those," said Nelson, whose lyrics draw on a
turbulent youth, three failed marriages and a period of professional drifting.
"I've been broke before and will be again. Heartbroke? That's serious. Lose a
few bucks? That's not.";   According to the Recording Industry Association of
America, only two of Nelson's four dozen previous albums sold more than 3
million copies: "Stardust" and "Always On My Mind.";   But Nelson has a
reservoir of good will that he can dip into, especially among farmers who
remember the Farm Aid concerts he helped organize in the 1980s.;   "If I
didn't like his music, I'd still buy the CD to help him because of the help
he's been to the farm organizations," said Benny Bunting, a mushroom grower in
Oak City, N.C.  </TEXT>
