<LEADPARA>  GET out the riot gear again. Guns N' Roses is about to cause another stir.
This time it won't be at your nearby stadium, however, but at your local
record store. On Tuesday, the group's two new albums, "Use Your Illusion I and
II," make their debut.;   The albums' release comes after months of delays,
four years after GN'R's debut studio record, "Appetite for Destruction" (which
has sold 14 million copies) and three years after the 6 million-selling EP "G
N' R Lies."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE ENDLESS APPETITE FOR GUNS N' ROSES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  MUSIC  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The hoopla and "numbers" surrounding the new records are equally stunning.
The group's label, Geffen, reports that approximately 1,000 record stores
around the country plan to open at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday -- to accommodate the
fans who just can't wait any longer -- and that various radio stations will be
broadcasting from those stores.;   Responding to the anticipated demand, the
company is also shipping 2 million copies of each of the albums in the United
States.;   And Saturday, Album Network, a music trade publication, is
sponsoring a satellite broadcast of a three-hour "listening party" focused on
the albums. The broadcast comes with interviews with GN'R that were recorded
at the Mustang Ranch near Reno.;   Now, about the albums: Each comes with 75
minutes of music, weighing in at a combined 30 songs and 2 1/2 hours of
gut-busting GN'R sound. Several of those songs were part of the group's
controversial U.S. tour this summer. "You Could Be Mine" (from "II") was part
of the soundtrack of the film "Terminator 2: Judgment Day" (released as the
album's first single, it sold 1 1/2 million copies in 30 days). And the ballad
"Don't Cry" (from "I") was released Sept. 3 as an advance for the albums.;
Could this be the event of the season? Possibly. It is the first time that a
group of this stature has released two albums of new material simultaneously.
And with the various delays, the fans' appetite for GN'R has reached a
screeching pitch. Now all the group has to do is live up to the moment with
its music. Will they do it? Tune in next week when we review the records.;
TOUR NEWS -- The halcyon days of techno-pop are now long gone, but one of the
finer groups from those days, Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark, is set to
begin its U.S. tour Sunday. They come to the D.N.A in San Francisco on Oct.
8.;   At the opposite end of pop from the synthesizer sound of techno-pop is
sweet soul music, and none is sweeter than that of soul-romantic Luther
Vandross. Vandross comes to the Bay Area for a show at the Oakland Coliseum
Arena, Oct. 24. Tickets go on sale Saturday (show times and ticket prices were
not available at press time).;   JAZZ AT FILOLI -- The final performance of
the Jazz at Filoli series is set for Saturday, and it's a winner. Legendary
vibraphonist Bobby Hutcherson will present his music, which spans several
generations of jazz from bop to the modal school. The performance -- which
also comes with a question-and-answer section with the illustrious jazzman --
begins at 1:30 p.m. at the Filoli Mansion, Canada Road, Woodside. Tickets are
$25, and the number to call is (415) 364-8300.;   JAZZ AGAIN -- The dates for
the next edition of the San Jose Jazz Festival have now been set: Aug. 7-9,
1992. The 1991 version, this past August, drew 35,000 fans to Plaza Park, the
largest crowd ever to come to an event at that location. Updates and
information about the 1992 festival are available from the San Jose Jazz
Society, at (408) 288-7557.;   ON WITH THE SHOWS -- On sale Sunday: tickets to
the Oct. 12 Day on the Green at the Oakland Coliseum Stadium. The event stars
Metallica, Faith No More, Soundgarden and Queensryche. Tickets are $28.50. And
Saturday, tickets go on sale for Procol Harum's show at the Palace of Fine
Arts in San Francisco, Oct. 3 at 8 p.m. Tickets are $18.50. These are the guys
who gave the world one of pop's greatest masterpieces, "A Whiter Shade of
Pale," back in 1967. Call (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277 for both shows.  </TEXT>
