<LEADPARA>  SONY Music has signed the rock group Aerosmith to one of the largest contracts
in the record business: about $30 million for four records, people involved in
the negotiations report.;    The deal comes shortly after Sony signed Michael
Jackson to a five-record, $25 million contract. The other major contracts in
the industry have been Janet Jackson's $32 million contract for three records
with Island Records and the Rolling Stones' $25 million contract with CBS
Records, signed in 1984.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SONY SIGNS AEROSMITH TO $30 MILLION RECORD
DEAL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Sony declined to comment on the terms of the deal, but a person close to
Aerosmith said the group would get about $10 million on signing and that there
was no timetable for delivery of the records.;    Aerosmith had been under
contract to Geffen Records, which is now owned by Matsushita Electrical Co.
and run by David Geffen.;    Geffen said Wednesday that he had the rights to
the group's next two studio albums and a greatest-hits album. "Traditionally
they make a record once every three or four years," he said. "At that rate
they will probably make their first record for Sony in 1995.";    Two
top-level record industry executives said they thought the deal was very risky
for Sony because the group members, including lead singer Steven Tyler and
lead guitarist Joe Perry, will be well into their 40s when they would start to
record for Sony.;    Aerosmith enjoyed tremendous popularity during the 1970s
with such Columbia Records albums as "Get Your Wings," "Toys in the Attic" and
"Rocks." Aerosmith has sold more than 30 million records at Columbia.;    But
the band's popularity waned after the departure of guitarist Joe Perry in
1979. Aerosmith persevered without the guitarist, but their post-Perry
recordings sold modestly. Perry reconciled with the band in the mid-'80s, and
the guitarist and Tyler underwent a well-documented drug-detox period.;
Aerosmith signed with Geffen Records in the mid-'80s and scored a remarkable
comeback with their "Permanent Vacation" album. The record sold 3 million
copies and featured radio-MTV hits like "Angel" and "Dude (Looks Like a
Lady)." A headline tour featuring Guns N' Roses was one of the
highest-grossing jaunts of the 1980s.;    The band's 1989 "Pump" album has
sold more than 6 million copies and yielded two top-five singles.  </TEXT>
