   Despite a sales slump in the record business, Virgin Music
Group signed a pricey new contract with the Rolling Stones,
and Time Warner Inc. is close to signing a deal that will
give Madonna millions more for every new record.
   With the expiration of the Stones' current recording
contract with Sony Corp., Virgin, based in London and part of
closely held Virgin Group of Cos., said it signed a
three-record deal with the group beginning in 1993. Terms
weren't disclosed, but industry executives valued the
agreement at more than $35 million. In addition to three new
records, Virgin Music will get the back catalog of Stones
albums from 1971 onward.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Stones deal had been rumored for weeks in the
industry. Sony's Sony Music unit had been negotiating with
the Stones for a new contract, but people familiar with the
talks said the company balked at paying the Stones' asking
price, concerned about the group's age -- the members are in
the 40s and 50s -- and future appeal to younger audiences. A
top Sony official declined to discuss the negotiations, other
than to say "we made an offer we thought was economic."
   Sony is believed to have paid the Stones $6 million in
advance for each of several albums in the 1980s; the new
Virgin agreement is said to raise those advances to $8
million. Sony Music, then CBS Records, made news by stealing
the Stones away from Atlantic Records in the early 1980s with
a deal that stunned the industry at the time. Some industry
executives speculate Sony lost money on some albums, but Sony
says the overall deal was profitable. Industry sources said
that while the Stones' most recent album, "Steel Wheels,"
sold about two million copies in the U.S. alone, the album
before that, "Undercover" is said to have sold less than one
million copies world-wide.
   In any case, Sony has put millions into two other
expensive gambles recently: its multi-media deal with Michael
Jackson reportedly worth more than $60 million to the pop
star, and a deal valued at more than $35 million with another
aging rock band, Aerosmith.
   But a number of other record companies apparently were
interested in the Stones, and bidders were said to include
PolyGram, 80% owned by Philips Electronics N.V. of the
Netherlands. Virgin, the largest independent label in the
record business, appears to be motivated by the lack of a
major rock act on a roster that includes pop singers Paula
Abdul and Janet Jackson.
   The Madonna deal with the Sire Records label, within
Warner Music Group, is a different matter; Madonna still owes
her label three records but was seeking a richer deal.
Negotiations have been dragging on for months, but a source
close to the company said that the Madonna contract may be
signed by year end. A new contract could include a jump in
advances to about $5 million per record from $3 million. In
addition, her royalty rate will rise to 20% from 18%,
industry sources said.
   The new 20% royalty rate for Madonna puts her below the
25% some superstars get, but her albums don't sell near as
many as Michael Jackson's, for example. Her last album, a
live concert recording, sold between seven and eight million
copies world-wide, while the last Jackson album sold 25
million world-wide. Sources close to the deal said that
Madonna's lawyers talked tough, but she had less bargaining
power since she still owed three records to her label. Two
more were added under the deal at the new fees.
   In addition, Madonna will be getting an undisclosed sum to
set up her own record label to record other acts, tentatively
to be called Home. Sources said Time Warner hasn't signed off
on the deal yet partly because it is still fine-tuning
clauses involving film deals and possible book deals. On the
movie side, Madonna is a riskier proposition; though she had
a role in the successful "Dick Tracy," most of her efforts --
such as "Who's That Girl" and "Shanghai Surprise" -- have
flopped.
   Still, of the two mega-deals, the Virgin/Stones deal has
raised more eyebrows in the music industry. The Madonna terms
are hefty but not unreasonable for a world-wide rock star who
is young and continues to re-invent herself. Virgin's future
is also in some question, as rumors persist that the company
is for sale.
   But yesterday, Richard Branson, the principal owner of the
Virgin companies, which include Virgin Atlantic airline,
released a statement denying persistent rumors that Virgin is
in talks to sell its music company to Thorn EMI PLC.
</TEXT>
