<LEADPARA>  IT'S been less than two years since Clint Black turned the country-music
industry on its ear, and already the 29-year-old singer/songwriter has more
than enough awards, ribbons, medals and gold records to fill an entire room.
But if there's one piece of booty the Texas phenom is proudest of, it's
probably the one that sits out in the garage.;    Back in 1989, when Black was
just another new kid in Nashville with a ready smile and a bagful of songs,
producer James Stroud told him, jokingly, "If you get me a gold record, you
can have my Porsche." Black's debutalbum, "Killin' Time," took off like a shot
from a howitzer -- going gold (500,000 copies) in five months, platinum (a
million copies) in nine months and double platinum (2 million copies) in 18
months. The new kid with the nice smile got his Porsche.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OUT OF THE BLUE, INTO THE BLACK
COUNTRY SINGER CLINT BLACK DIDN'T WASTE ANY
TIME MAKING SUCCESS LOOK AS EASY AS A SMILE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
See also related article on page 14A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "I love that car," said Black, in a phone call from Nashville last week.
"Before we start the next album, I'm going up to take a look at his house.";
 Black, whose tour with Merle Haggard and Carlene Carter rolls through the Cow
Palace in Daly City tonight, is currently the hottest name in country music.
With James Dean looks, a crisp, pared-down musical style and gentle,
self-effacing humor, Black is the embodiment of the new traditionalist
movement that's pumping new life into the once-moribund country scene.;
Black's conquest of the country-music industry has been so complete and so
lightning-fast it makes Operation Desert Storm seem like the Peloponnesian War
by comparison. Black's stats are beyond any record executive's wildest dream:
"Killin' Time" occupied the No. 1 slot on the Billboard country-album chart
for 31 weeks and produced five No. 1 singles. The first single, "A Better
Man," was the first debut single to top the country chart in 15 years. The
album even moved onto Billboard's Top-40 pop-album chart.;    In November,
while "Killin' Time" was still in the No. 1 slot, RCA Records released Black's
latest album, "Put Yourself in My Shoes." It sold a million copies in a month.
Today, "Put Yourself in My Shoes" is at No 2 on the country-album chart, and
"Killin' Time" is still at No. 9, almost two years after its release.;
Lately it seems as if Black has spent more time at award shows than at
concerts: In '89 the country industry's Blackest season began with the Country
Music Association's Horizon Award -- given to the most promising newcomer.
Last October, he bagged the association's best-male-vocalist and
best-new-touring-artist prizes. Last April, he swept through four top
categories at the Academy of Country Music's annual awards: best album, best
single, best new male vocalist and best male vocalist.;    The blizzard of
accolades continues, and Black stays the course. "I don't feel pressure from
the awards and the polls and the charts. Those things are just a hand up the
ladder. The real pressure I feel is whenever I'm in the studio and close to
finishing a record," he said. "Making critical decisions then is always tough.
I would have liked to have a lot more time with the last album, but I'm
realistic about it. In order to spend more time in the studio, I would have
had to pass up some of the other things I've done.";    Black's lyric
stock-in-trade is songs about good women who leave too soon and bad jobs that
don't end soon enough. "People always saw me as a good-hearted guy looking at
the bright side of things. A guy smiling through the pain. And it put me in a
really good light," said Black, straining to find an explanation for his
meteoric rise.;    Not long ago, few people would have ever wanted to put
themselves in Black's shoes: "There was never a time I doubted I was meant to
be in this business," said Black, who began working the Houston honky-tonk
circuit straight out of high school. "But there was a time when I realized I
should get some other work in order to rest my voice. There was no way I could
go into a studio and record anything decent after working six straight nights
in a bar. Three long sets -- hundreds of songs -- night in and night out,
really chewed me up." His day jobs included gigs as an ironworker and a
fishing guide.;    "The moment I realized things were really taking off was in
May of '87, when I met Bill Ham (the Houston-based manager-producer of the
rock group ZZ Top). Right then I knew," said Black, who still lives in Houston
and is considering a second home in Nashville. "I called my mom and dad and
said 'this is it.' " Six months after his first meeting with Ham, Black was
signed to RCA.;    Black said his own biggest responsibility is building good,
radio-worthy songs. "A lot of times (a song) will just begin with a musical
idea; then I'll build the structure and add the lyrics," said Black. "In a few
cases, a page of lyrics come first, but for the most part, I look for the
musical hook. It's like a jigsaw puzzle: You lay all your pieces out, start
with the perimeter and work in from there.";    Up until now, longtime
guitarist and collaborator Hayden Nicholas shared writing credit on about half
of Black's recorded works. Black said he's also currently working with pop
writer Jerry Williams (whose works have been recorded by Eric Clapton and the
Fabulous Thunderbirds) and is planning to link up with middle-of-the-road
ballad-baron Michael Bolton at the end of March.;    "It'd be great (to have a
pop hit), but I'm not shootin' for that," Black said. "Radio's idea of what
fits a pop format is opening up -- thanks largely to people like the Eagles.
They proved you can use some country elements and make them fit on rock radio.
But I'd still probably have to change the instrumentation on my albums.";
Hunk appeal;  If Black's mass exposure came only through radio and CDs, it
would be easy to say his phenomenal appeal stems solely from his talent as a
great singer/songwriter. But there's something else at work in Black's case:
the Hunk Factor. Women -- and not just wailing teeny-boppers -- go wild over
the wide-shouldered, clean-cut honky-tonk hero. In a matter of months, Black
has elbowed his way into the country pantheon of male sex symbols that
includes Randy Travis, Ricky Van Shelton and George Strait. Last week, US
magazine proclaimed Black to be one of the world's 10 sexiest bachelors.;
"I try to stay out of the crowds, but onstage is different," said Black, who
seems genuinely perplexed by the Hunk Factor. "I'll never get used to it in
concert when they begin screaming like that. My drummer hears a lot of things,
and he tells me what the women are talking about," Black said, laughing. "He
says they're always talking about the eyes. I guess it worked for Roy Rogers,
right? And let's face it -- people like people who smile.";    Black's current
tour, which began two weeks ago in Fort Worth, Texas, is his first national
outing as a headline act. "When I was out with (the group) Alabama last year,
for the most part it was 10 months of working middle slot," said Black. "A lot
has changed, really, now that I'm closing the show. I've got my own stage, and
I even get to decide what we eat," he said, laughing.;    The main event;
When it came to discussing the support role living legend Merle Haggard plays
on this tour, Black was diplomatic: "Yeah, it feels strange, and it feels
great to be in this position. I'd never imagined that in all my years I would
see this. But if it were flipped around the other way, with me opening for
him, it'd still be great. It's just great to be closing the show, great to
know you're the reason that people came there.;    "There's no way I could
have known even three years ago what this was going to be like," said Black.
"I wish I had appreciated my obscurity more when I had it. I never thought I'd
long for the times I could go anywhere and just be a face in the crowd.
Really, I should have savored the days when I was just another smiling face.";
   After winning virtually every award in the industry as a freshman, what
conquest could possibly be left for the good guy in the black hat? "The road
-- that's the only thing. For now.";    Clint Black; With Merle Haggard and
Carlene Carter; When: 8 tonight; Where: Cow Palace, Geneva Avenue and Santos
Street, Daly City; Tickets: $20.50 reserved; (408) 998-2277, (415) 762-2277  </TEXT>
