   NEW YORK -- Call it "Madonna meets Wonder Woman on Wall
Street."
   By day, the new Marvel comic book heroine Nightcat has a
gig as aspiring pop singer Jacqueline Tavarez. By night, she
stalks the city in skin-tight leather and slices up bad guys.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In real life, though, Jackie Tavarez actually is a
struggling singer who performs under the moniker Nightcat.
Her promoters, trying to get her noticed, have linked her
image to an alter-ego super heroine, signing Marvel Comics
legend Stan Lee to create a comic book all her own.
   Sound weird? There's more. Ms. Tavarez's backers have set
up a publicly held company, dubbed Black Cat Entertainment
Co., to profit from her many exploits. In addition to the
live performer and the comic book, there is a Nightcat record
album, and a video is in the works. "It's as if Madonna were
a public company," says Black Cat's chairman, Charles Stein.
   Except that Jackie Tavarez is a long way from being a pop
star. Her debut album still hasn't sold out its first run of
just 25,000 copies.
   But the new comic book has the makings of a hit.
Nightcat's premiere issue, which went on sale in early April,
has already sold out its initial run of 70,000 copies. For
the debut issue of a $3.95 heavystock book, that is "a very
good, strong sale," says a spokeswoman for Marvel Comics. A
typical Spiderman or Superman, by comparison, might sell half
a million copies but retails for only $1 and is printed on
cheaper paper.
   The idea of making a comic book character a pop star isn't
new. More than two decades ago, "Archie" gave rise to the
Archies, who sang one of the most saccharine hits of all
time, "Sugar, Sugar." In the late '70s, going in reverse,
Marvel produced a series of comic books based on the
heavymetal band Kiss. And this year, Time Warner Inc.'s DC
Comics unit is creating a fantasy comic book for rock star
Prince, who tours this summer.
   Buyers of the premiere issue of "Nightcat" get lots of
violence, a little bondage, the obligatory mad scientist --
and plenty of skin. The heroine wears thigh-high stiletto
boots and a skimpy, black leather top that laces up the
center, similar to the get-up Ms. Tavarez wears -- in real
life -- on stage. "It looks like an S&amp;M outfit," the
21-yearold singer concedes.
   In the first issue's climactic scene, Nightcat, armed with
new powers after an accidental injection of "cat serum,"
battles a scantily clad villainess on the roof of a
skyscraper to avenge her father's death. "I dunno, for a
modern, happening chick, you sure sound like a dork]" the
Nightcat taunts. "Now that we've finished discussing my
verbal proclivities," her nemesis retorts, "you may prepare
to die]"
   If the project catches on, Black Cat Entertainment could
post some pretty profits. The comic book market this year is
expected to approach $500 million at retail, according to
Comics Buyer's Guide. A strong character can sell up to
500,000 copies a month.
   More importantly, the typical comic-book buyer is likely
to be part of the biggest chunk of the music-buying market:
males from teen-agers to 30-year-olds. The new company will
get a 5% share of comic-book sales and an 8% cut of album
revenue. The singer herself receives a fourth of Black Cat's
take.
   The comic book promotion was the brainchild of Ms.
Tavarez's manager, Don Kessler. He approached Mr. Lee, the
chairman of Marvel Comics and creator of the Incredible Hulk,
Spidey and a passel of other super heroes.
   Mr. Lee met with the young singer and immediately felt she
had "something feline-seeming" about her. The story line uses
the singer's real name and has her sing lyrics from her
songs. It also engages in a bit of wishful thinking, with one
page showing the Nightcat gracing magazine covers, including
Time's. And it introduces a funky new sound effect --
"Snik-Snik," when Nightcat unleashes her talons.
   Ms. Tavarez, for her part, had wanted to be a journalist.
But she found success in modeling in high school, making her
mark saying "Fayva wow]" in TV commercials for the shoe
company.
   The aspiring singer, who was born in the Dominican
Republic and raised in the tough Bushwick section of
Brooklyn, gushes at the chance to "express myself for good
things." In subsequent issues of the comic book, she says,
she hopes to focus more on her Hispanic background and
address more socially significant issues.
</TEXT>
