<HEAD>Civil Libertarians See National Effect from Obscenity Ruling</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with record store owner being
arrested, quotes from him and sheriff's spokesman. Picks up 8th graf
pvs: `The recording ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's obscenity ruling against a 2 Live Crew rap
album has no legal effect outside south Florida, where a record
store owner was arrested today, but civil libertarians see a
practical effect spreading nationally.
   ``This does pose a real threat that the amount of obscenity
actions may increase around the country,'' New York attorney Floyd
Abrams, a First Amendment expert, said Thursday. ``It is a direct
threat to freedom of expression in the arts, as well as in music in
particular.''
   U.S. District Judge Jose Gonzalez ruled Wednesday that the lyrics
of the Miami group's sexually explicit album ``As Nasty As They Want
To Be'' are obscene, leaving area retailers liable for arrest for
sales of the platinum-selling record.
   Today, a Fort Lauderdale area record store owner was arrested on
an obscenity charge after selling the album. Broward County
sheriff's deputies arrested E-C Records owner Charles Freeman at his
store less than three hours after he received a shipment of 25
copies.
   ``America is free, free for everybody,'' Freeman said. ``And as
long as this is America and I'm not living in Cuba, I feel my rights
are violated.''
   An undercover officer went in to buy copies of the record and
tape, then uniformed officers entered the store to make the arrest.
   ``I would have to say that the research and the consultation that
we were doing has apparently been concluded and we're prepared to
enforce it,'' sheriff's spokesman Jim Leljedal said minutes after
the arrest.
   Before authorities arrived, Freeman said he had sold all but six
copies of the recording. He said a line had formed outside the shop
in anticipation of the shipment's arrival.
   ``I'll go to jail, and I'll come back and sell it again,'' he
said before deputies arrived. ``I opened up a record store three
years ago expecting to sell records and this was the furthest thing
from my mind.''
   Asked why he would challenge the ban, Freeman explained: ``I'm a
small independent. All my money is going to be made on R&amp;B and rap,
so it'll hurt me in the long run.''
   The recording industry generally favors warning stickers on album
covers to bring attention to lyrics that some might consider
objectionable.
   But Michael Greene, president of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, said he hoped the specter of censorship
raised by the Fort Lauderdale ruling would act as a unifying force.
   ``This ruling, alongside the chilling lyrics legislation which is
making the rounds through the statehouses nationwide, must serve as
a call to mobilize all who value basic artistic freedom and who are
willing to tenaciously fight for the protection of First Amendment
rights,'' Greene said.
   Bruce Jesse, vice president of advertising and sales promotion
for the 265-store Wherehouse record store chain based in Los
Angeles, concluded, ``You're putting the retailer at a significant
risk.''
   But Bruce Fein, former counsel general of the Federal
Communications Commission, saw a limited impact, saying, ``I don't
think this sets a nationwide precedent that will cause all off-color
rock music to be banned.''
   Supplies of 2 Live Crew's disputed record dried up in South
Florida as the obscenity case was argued, but the decision is widely
expected to boost sales elsewhere.
   ``The lesson of history has always been, if you tell people you
can't have anything, they want it all the more,'' said Nova
University law professor Bruce Rogow. He represented 2 Live Crew in
its lawsuit against Broward County Sheriff Nick Navarro over his
threat to prosecute retailers.
   The decision had no effect on the group's plans for two shows
Saturday night at Club Futura in nearby Hollywood.
   Club owner Kenneth Gerringer told City Council members Thursday
that the opening show would be a tame performance for all age
groups, and he would ask the rappers to shun explicit lyrics in the
later adults-only show.
   Ten uniformed police officers will be working inside and outside
the club, primarily for crowd control, said Paul Dungan,
administrative assistant to the police chief, who was out of town.
   ``We're handling this as if Michael Jackson were coming to town,
or Dean Martin or any of the top stars,'' he said. ``I would not
advise officers to go up on the stage and arrest four people in
front of 1,000 people.''
   But Mayor Sal Oliveri gave Gerringer a stern warning to pass
along to 2 Live Crew, saying, ``Artist or no artist, I don't want
Hollywood to have the reputation, in my opinion, that we have
obscene entertainment.''
</TEXT>
