<HL>
   Female Rappers Sing
   Of Smut and Spice
   And Nothing Nice
   ---
   They Make It in Men's World
   By Being Rude and Nasty
   Especially to Each Other
   ----
   By Meg Cox
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/11/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Rap music has been around for years,
   Street-life epics and macho jeers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Black men dominated for ever so long.
   But now black women are coming on strong.


   PITTSBURGH -- Backed by an all-girl band at the Syria
Mosque concert hall here, Salt and Pepa are acting out their
rap "Independent." The two young women swing briefcases and
pretend they're heading off to work, while they yell at two
men in aprons, "Those dishes better be washed]"
   They rap about making money and not needing to lean on
men. "You had to cross me, and now you lost me," one of the
women chants. "Get off me, softy. I'm the boss, see?"
   Teen-age girls in the audience are nodding, chanting and
raising their fists. Jada James, an 18-year-old fan who works
in a Pittsburgh blood bank, says approvingly of the women on
stage, "They have made it in a man's world, which rap is."
   Or was. Salt-N-Pepa has sold 3.5 million albums since
1987, including the memorably titled "A Salt With a Deadly
Pepa." Its success is credited for spawning an industry rush
to sign other promising women.
   After more than a decade of explosive sales growth for
male rappers, women are a hot commodity. In fact, some are
positively steamy.
   There is, for instance, the group Hoes Wit Attitude, whose
first rap album was the scene setter, "Livin' in a Hoe
House." A typical performance begins when the three women
rappers strut onto a smoke-shrouded stage wearing mink coats.
As the smoke lifts, so do the clothes -- the three strip off
their minks to reveal skimpy black-leather bikinis studded
with rhinestones.
   Their raps, with titles like "Trick Is a Trick," exhaust
the rhyming possibilities of four-letter words, but not the
fans: The Hoes' first album has sold 100,000 copies in its
first eight months.
   Although the audience may be tickled by such risque raps,
some of the female trailblazers in the genre are not.
   Salt and Pepa, for instance, when interviewed backstage
after their act in Pittsburgh, slam their bikini-clad
competitors. "Explicit lyrics just aren't ladylike," says
Salt, a former Sears telephone clerk from New York's Queens
borough whose real name is Cheryl James. "Cursing and
carrying on and saying every disgusting thing is just a
gimmick."
   Gimmick or no, the gutter girls are a growing fad in one
of the trendiest corners of the fad-hungry commercial music
world. Already the Hoes have company. A duo called "Bytches
With Problems" (BWP for short) released its first album of
filthy lyrics in February; it sold 80,000 copies in its first
week.
   But some critics, such as Dream Hampton, who writes for a
rap magazine called The Source, have been outraged by the
Hoes' lyrics. Scandalized by a rap about a sex hotline which
includes the line: "Poor Mandela, just gettin' home, calling
up a hoe on the telephone," Ms. Hampton asked in her review,
"Is nothing sacred]?]" She went on to attack the group for
perpetuating "negative stereotypes of women" and marketing
themselves "like extras in a porn flick."
   The controversy has hit academia, too. At a recent
conference at Howard University on "hip hop," as black pop
cultural expressions like break-dancing, graffiti and rap are
called, both the Hoes and the Bytches withdrew from a panel
about explicit women rappers. The Hoes' spokesman said one of
the women was sick. But the Bytches' manager admitted he was
fearful of a confrontation. The meeting might have become a
verbal brawl if the groups had come, concedes Aarian Pope,
one of the student organizers of the conference.
   "There were people who came to curse these sisters out,"
says Ms. Pope. "These {groups} are being irresponsible.
They're making money, but with all the other problems of the
black community, we don't need these negative women
disrespecting themselves. Other panelists told fans at the
conference: `Don't buy this stuff.'"
   The hostilities are also spilling over into the music. A
rapper felicitously named Harmony knocked risque women
rappers on her album last fall -- though her choice of words
wasn't exactly pristine. "I ain't no slut that sells records
with her butt," goes one line. Harmony, whose real name is
Pamela Scott, says, "We need to lift ourselves up and move to
more positive things. Why be a `bitch with a problem'? If you
had a problem, wouldn't you want to solve it?"
   The Bytches and Hoes don't even have nice things to say
about each other. Lyndah and Tanisha Michelle, who perform in
street clothes as the Bytches, say, "We're not trying to sell
records with sex like the Hoes: We're selling reality."
   The Hoes counter: "I'd rather be someone making money than
another word for dog."
   Both groups insist they're actually true feminists: trying
to present an image of women as strong, successful and in
control.
   "So someone calls you a bitch?" says Tanisha of BWP.
"That's what they call any woman who's tough and good at
business. We say, wear the title as a badge of honor and keep
getting yours."
   And Kim "Baby Girl" Kenner, leader of the Hoes, says that
growing up on the south side of Chicago, she and her
girlfriends called each other "hoe" as a joking term of
familiarity and she doesn't regard it as degrading. The
25-year-old says she was selling real estate for Century-21
in Chicago when she started the group, first called Sleaze
Patrol, with her sister and her cousin. "They use sexy women
to sell cars -- what's wrong with being sexy to sell
records?" she asks.
   Some industry insiders dismiss these foul-mouthed ladies
as mere copycats whose labels are trying to capitalize on
last year's controversy over harshly explicit albums by
groups like 2 Live Crew, Geto Boys and NWA (which stands for
"Niggers With Attitude"). These male groups perform so-called
gangster rap, a violent, misogynistic depiction of gang life
in the housing projects.
   A staple of gangster rap is graphic revenge fantasies
about rival gangs, women and police. The Bytches, for
instance, just bought the exclusive rights to the widely
shown home videotape of the Los Angeles police beating a
black motorist, which they want for the video version of
their rap single about police brutality "Wanted."
   The Bytches also have two raps about killing men. In one,
"Comin' Back Strapped," the girls execute some men in a
drive-by shooting because one guy makes a suggestive remark.
   "Right now, it's still a novelty to have women rappers
saying the outrageous things guys said before," says Janine
McAdams, R&amp;B music editor for Billboard magazine. "But except
for a few adolescents who always have to buy what's illicit,
I'm betting that sex rap will fall by the wayside."
   Even if that happens, some of the more reputable female
rappers may still be standing. One is likely to be Queen
Latifah (la-TEE-fah), a big-boned 20-year-old from Newark,
N.J., known for her African turbans and crowns. She sells out
concerts in Europe and Japan and has lectured at Harvard. Her
first album, "All Hail the Queen," has sold more than a
million copies world-wide since its release a year and a half
ago.
   So it seems that women rappers are here to stay -- and
even the most notorious gangster rappers are wising up to
that. On his album "AmeriKKKa's Most Wanted," rapper "Ice
Cube" asks "Yo-Yo," a 19-year-old woman rapper with a
feminist slant, to duel with him verbally in a number called
"It's a Man's World."
   In the refrain, Ice Cube says, "This is a man's world,
thank you very much," and Yo-Yo replies: "But it wouldn't be
a damn thing without a woman's touch." Now, he's producing
her albums.
</TEXT>
