<HL> 'New Age' Music Wins Wider Following
As Many People Grow Too Old for Rock
---
By Meg Cox
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/01/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> MOVIES, RECORDS, RECORDING STUDIOS (FLX) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Even its fans sometimes call it "audio Valium" or "yuppie elevator music."
Yet "New Age" music -- mostly instrumental, mellow and melodic, and sometimes electronic -- is catching on.

   Often carrying such meditative titles as "Deep Breakfast" and "In Search of the Turtle's Navel," New Age pieces have moved out of cultdom and into the musical mainstream.
Until recently, most New Age records were produced by small, independent record labels that got little attention from record stores and none from commercial radio.
Now, though New Age hardly threatens to outmuscle rock, it is beginning to command a widespread following.

   The pioneer independent New Age label, Windham Hill of Palo Alto, Calif., had sales of $30 million last year.
Little labels such as Private Music and Cinema Records, both less than two years old, are being snapped up, into distribution deals, by major record companies.
Record stores across the country are adding New Age bins.
And last month the first Grammy Award for New Age music went to Andreas Vollenweider, a Swiss harpist with two gold records on the CBS label.

   Even radio has tuned in.
For at least three years there had been a few scattered New Age programs around the country, shoehorned inside rock or jazz formats.
Then, on Valentine's Day this year, one major Los Angeles radio station -- which 19 years ago helped pioneer so-called album-oriented rock -- switched full time to New Age and other music it calls "light, hypnotic, uplifting."
No longer KMET, the station now is KTWV -- "The WAVE."
Since then, "beautiful-music" station KLRS, in Santa Cruz, Calif., has gone New Age.
In early April, CBS Radio will begin nationally syndicating a weekly two-hour New Age program, "The New Era."

   "Rock is great when the hormones are raging through you, but tastes change as you grow up," says Frank Cody, the program director for KTWV in Los Angeles.
He adds: "I've never seen a response like we're getting already.
We get these elegant letters written on word processors."

   Surveys by Windham Hill show the average age of those who buy its records is around 32, and that New Age listeners tend to be urban and upscale.
Anne Robinson, who co-founded Windham Hill 11 years ago and still runs it, says the music establishment kept on making rock records, mostly for teen-agers, long after baby boomers hit their 20s and 30s.
"Now they realize there is this whole segment of population with discretionary income they haven't been supplying records for," she says.

   For years, Windham Hill and other labels couldn't get their records distributed through normal channels.
Ms. Robinson says the New Age term was applied because at first, record sales were mostly through small independent bookstores, and an early Windham Hill booster was a magazine called "New Age."

   Quality was what spread the word beyond the tofu-and-granola crowd: Many New Age fans first heard the music at stereo stores, which used the high-quality pressings to show off high-end equipment.
Audiophiles love effects like those on the Living Music label, which records in such places as the Grand Canyon and inside a reverberant stone cathedral.

   One New Age label noted especially for sound quality is American Gramaphone, in Omaha, Neb.
The eclectic musical approach of founder-producer-composer Chip Davis tells a lot about the history and attraction of the music.
Though he is a classically trained musician who once played bassoon in the Toledo (Ohio) Symphony, Mr. Davis has had an unconventional music career that included a stint as a jingle writer in Omaha.
A country-and-western-style commercial he wrote for Old Home Bread, about a bread-truck driver, was so popular that Mr. Davis started making country records.
One, "Convoy," sold seven million copies.

   That success allowed Mr. Davis to start his own label, American Gramaphone, about a decade ago, to record instrumental music he had been writing for his own pleasure.
He called his pieces "baroque rock."
They combined classical forms with a sometimes-rock beat.
They were played on historical instruments, including harpsichords built by his father, along with drums and synthesizers.

   He called his albums "Fresh Aire."
To record them he assembled studio musicians known as the "Mannheim Steamroller" group.

   Mr. Davis, a soft-spoken long-haired man of 39, is obsessed with each step of record-making.
One Fresh Aire album begins with a Gregorian chant recorded in a cathedral and continues with a Chip Davis composition performed by the London Symphony Orchestra, conducted by Mr. Davis.
All his records weigh at least 120 grams, well above the average 90 to 100, so less warping occurs and the records last longer.
Record sleeves and jackets are thick, with fancy graphics.

   All this costs a lot.
The first American Gramaphone records bore suggested retail prices of $17.95. (The prices have since declined to $12.95, still considerably above most conventional vinyl records.)
Prices for the company's compact disks also sell at premiums.
Despite the high prices, little advertising and no radio play, audiophiles discovered the label.
By last year, annual sales topped $5 million.

   One fan, Eric Sjorgen, a 31-year-old New Jersey pharmacist who calls himself "an audio nut, a fanatic," says: "I first heard the Fresh Aire albums at a stereo store.
The music was different and the fidelity was great.
The tranquility of the music calmed me.
I have every record and compact disk they ever did."
On top of that, Mr. Sjorgen had the music played at his wedding.

   Mr. Davis hopes to reach an even wider audience with the album he just finished, his 23rd.
It features guitarist Mason Williams, best known for a runaway instrumental hit in 1968 called "Classical Gas," which Mr. Davis says was one of his principal inspirations.
That song, a catchy tune meshing classical guitar, harpsichord and violins with synthesizer and drums, was re-recorded for the new album, due out in the fall.
If the Mason Williams record "goes gold" by attaining sales of 500,000, as Mr. Davis hopes, it would be his label's second gold album.
Only a handful of New Age records have sold so well.

   Opinions differ as to just how vast the New Age market will become with radio and record-industry support.
"I think this is going to be a major factor for years to come," says Lee Abrams, an Atlanta media consultant who persuaded the Santa Cruz station to try New Age, on the basis of consumer research.
"This will become mood radio for the new mainstream."
But a spokeswoman for CBS Records, a division of CBS Inc., says, "There is almost a glut of New Age music.
I think there's a danger of boredom creeping in."

   One thing is sure: The critics haven't fallen in love with New Age.
"The music is bloodless, just a notch above elevator music," says Patrick Goldstein, an entertainment writer for the Los Angeles Times.
"But it's a wonderful demographic idea.
Record buyers are older.
They are looking for softer, more-soothing music."

</TEXT>
