<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Lots of Goals Left for Reba McEntire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reba McEntire is the only singer ever
voted female vocalist of the year four times by the Country Music
Association.
   She has performed live for millions She has a platinum album
(more than a million copies sold) for her ``Greatest Hits.'' She's
won a Grammy, appeared on three Bob Hope TV specials and branched
out into acting.
   What's left?
   ``Everything,'' she said. ``We want to sell more tickets and
more albums. Do movies and television. Produce records. Have a
bigger publishing company. Have more acts for my company.
   ``We've got lots to do.''
   McEntire, 35, who took off five months to have her first baby in
February, has had six straight gold albums, and was voted best
female country vocalist from 1984-87.
   She's in the midst of a 115-city concert tour that began May 3.
Her 17th album, ``Rumor Has It,'' has just been released.
   She recently acted in her first movie, ``Tremors,'' appearing as
a survivalist with star Kevin Bacon.
   ``I like to act and I want to pursue it more,'' she said in an
interview in her office a few days after singing at the Goodwill
Games in Seattle. ``Of course music and touring is No. 1.''
   Her single, ``Walk On,'' reached No. 2 on the country music
charts in July. It was about persevering during hard times, and
joined other topical issues she previously has tackled: ``The
Stairs'' was about wife abuse, and ``Am I the Only One Who Cares''
dealt with teen-age suicide and alienation.
   ``Fancy,'' in her new album, is about a mother pushing a girl
into prostitution to get ahead in life.
   ``I chose it because I liked it,'' McEntire said. ``I've wanted
to record it for five years.''
   Her 1987 Grammy was for ``Whoever's in New England.'' Her other
hit records include ``Cathy's Clown,'' ``New Fool at an Old Game,''
``Little Rock,'' ``Love Will Find Its Way to You,'' ``One Promise
Too Late'' and ``What Am I Gonna Do About You.''
   McEntire recently was co-host of ABC's ``Good Morning America,''
filling in for Joan Lunden who was on vacation. She appeared on the
Hope specials on NBC during the past few years.
   ``He liked me, and he likes to work with people he gets along
with and are easy to work with,'' McEntire said. ``We were told to
be there at a certain time, and we were there, usually early.''
   McEntire was the third of four children who grew up in Chockie,
Okla., where she mixed ranching, rodeoing and singing. She is a
former rodeo barrel racer and spent several years on a ranch in
Stringtown, Okla.
   She first appeared on country music charts in 1976, one year
after she gained notice by singing the National Anthem at the
National Rodeo Finals in Oklahoma City.
   But McEntire wasn't always on top. ``I've been booed off stage.
At times I haven't drawn flies. I've sat in a store to sign
autographs and someone asked me where the bathroom is!''
   Nevertheless, her string of four straight honors as country
music's top female singer likely will never be matched. Looking
back on it today, she's actually relieved K.T. Oslin finally
displaced her as the winner.
   ``It would have been sudden death for me if I had won it
again,'' McEntire said. ``You don't want to ride a good horse to
death.''
   She dismissed a story in a supermarket tabloid that she and
Oslin, best known for her hit record ``80s Ladies,'' are feuding.
   ``It was good that K.T. won. She is spunky and she brought
something to country music that we all needed, something totally
different. I really appreciate K.T.''
   Having a child has made her career even more meaningful to her.
   ``I have something to work for now that I have Shelby: to
accumulate more, allow him to be secure if something happens to
me.''
</TEXT>
