<LEADPARA>  RADIO stations won't play it. A record store chain banned it. The British
government seized it.;    The obscenity-laced album "Niggaz4Life" from rappers
N.W.A. isn't popular with a lot of people -- except record buyers, who have
made it the nation's favorite album, buying 954,000 copies in its first weeks
of release.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FOUL-MOUTHED SOCIAL COMMENTARY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Recordings  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     N.W.A. stands for Niggers With Attitude, and it's that angry, rebellious
attitude that sells. "It's absolutely the music that nobody's parents can
understand," said Jerry Heller, N.W.A.'s manager.;    "Niggaz4Life" boils over
with urban rage, the songs so peppered with profanity and images of sexual
violence they eventually numb the ears.;    It's an unsettling combination of
social commentary and foul mouths. N.W.A. has wide appeal, with whites buying
the album far more frequently than blacks, Heller said.;    Women are freely
described as "bitches" and "whores." Male sexual gratification -- and sexual
assault of females -- anchor more than half the album's songs. Police are
scum.;    Blacks are called "niggers" without pause, the word rattled off
scores of times before the album's last song winds down. About the only words
that can be quoted from one song are its title: "To Kill a Hooker.";    The
110-store WaxWorks chain banned the album from its outlets in 37 states. About
5,000 copies of "Niggaz4Life" were seized by Scotland Yard authorities from a
warehouse outside London in early June because the album allegedly violated
the Obscene Publications Act.;    Unlike the raunchy-for-no-reason party raps
of the 2 Live Crew, N.W.A.'s musical brutality can be traced to the real-life
urban catastrophe from which the band members sprang.;    Eazy-E, who leads
N.W.A. with a distinctive high-pitched voice, is a former drug dealer. The
band's M.C. Ren complains that he's hassled by police wherever he goes, and
he's fled gang-plagued Compton, a Los Angeles suburb, for safer environs.
Other band members include D.J. Yella and Dr. Dre.;    "It don't make no sense
to stay in the area when you know you can get shot at every day, get robbed
and killed," Ren said. "If you have the money to move, you should move.";
In their first album, the equally raunchy "Straight Outta Compton," N.W.A.
painted their ghetto home in colorful images that made drive-by-shootings,
drugs and police harassment part of a vivid, violent tableau. It sold 2
million copies.;    In 1989, Matt Ahlerich, the FBI's assistant director for
public affairs, said in a letter to N.W.A.'s record label that "advocating
violence and assault is wrong, and we in the law enforcement community take
exception to such action.";    N.W.A. couldn't have asked for a better
endorsement.;    With their most recent release, they examine the group's own
fame, sing about sex and drugs and blast the police again. Said Heller: "Until
our society solves the inner-city problems, they won't be hurting for
material.";    N.W.A.'s music blasts past the smooth rhythm and blues textures
behind the softer sounds of rappers such as M.C. Hammer. Although their latest
album is well-produced, mixing traditional street raps sounds with calypso and
audio effects, it's still raw.;    "There's so much bull out like old groups
trying to make comebacks and rappers doing R &amp; B. Every rap group that's
coming out now is pop," said N.W.A.'s M.C. Ren.;    Why is N.W.A. popular?
"People identify with their own street life," said M.C. Ren. "There are a lot
of different situations that they can relate to because they went through that
same (stuff) growing up."  </TEXT>
